import java.util.* ;
import java.io.*; 
public class Solution {
    public static int findAngle(int hour, int minute) {
        //Write your code here

        double minAngle = 6 * minute;
        double hourAngle = 30 * hour + 0.5 * minute;

        double angle = Math.abs(hourAngle - minAngle);

        angle = Math.min(angle,360 - angle);

        return (int)Math.floor(angle);
    }
}

Given the time in hours and minutes, you need to calculate the angle between the hour hand and the minute hand.
Note :
There can be two angles between the hour hand and minute hand, you need to print a minimum of two. Also, print the floor value of angle i.e. if the angle is 15.2, you need to print 15.



✅ Logic (Important Formula)

1. Minute hand angle from 12: minuteAngle = 6 × minute
(Because 360° / 60 = 6° per minute)

2. Hour hand angle from 12:
hourAngle=30 × hour + 0.5 × minute
(Because 360° / 12 = 30° per hour and hour hand moves 0.5° per minute)

3. Find difference: angle =  ∣ hourAngle − minuteAngle ∣

4. Take minimum of two angles:  angle=min(angle,360−angle)

5. Return floor value
